5. Core Components
Frontend

The frontend provides role-based user interfaces.

Supported portals:

Patient Portal
Doctor Portal
Reception Portal
Laboratory Portal
Clinic Admin Portal
Super Admin Portal

Responsibilities:

User Interface
Form Validation
Dashboard Rendering
API Communication
Authentication Token Management
Backend

The backend contains all business logic.

Responsibilities:

Authentication
Authorization
Business Rules
Data Validation
API Services
Event Publishing
Audit Logging
Database

The database acts as the primary source of truth.

Stores:

Patients
Doctors
Appointments
Consultations
Prescriptions
Lab Reports
Payments
Notifications
Audit Logs
Cache

Redis will be used for:

Frequently accessed reference data
Session-related caching (if needed)
Rate limiting
OTP storage
Short-lived application state
Background Processing

Background workers process tasks that should not delay user requests.

Examples:

Email notifications
SMS
WhatsApp
Report generation
Future AI processing
6. Functional Modules

The backend is organized into independent modules.

Authentication

↓

Patient

↓

Doctor

↓

Appointment

↓

Consultation

↓

Prescription

↓

Laboratory

↓

Payment

↓

Notification

↓

Reports

Each module owns its business logic and APIs.

7. Request Lifecycle

Example: Appointment Booking

Patient

↓

Frontend

↓

Appointment API

↓

Validation

↓

Database Transaction

↓

Appointment Saved

↓

Frontend Response

↓

Background Event Published

↓

Notification Worker

↓

Email/SMS Sent

The user receives confirmation immediately while notifications are processed asynchronously.

8. Multi-Tenant Architecture

Clinora is designed as a multi-tenant SaaS platform.

Each clinic has:

Independent users
Independent doctors
Independent patients
Independent appointments
Independent reports
Independent billing

Every request carries tenant information.

All data access is automatically filtered using the tenant identifier.

No tenant can access another tenant's information.

9. Authentication Flow
Login

↓

Authentication

↓

JWT Token

↓

Frontend Stores Token

↓

API Calls

↓

Authorization

↓

Business Logic

Future enhancements:

Multi-Factor Authentication
Single Sign-On
Google Login
Microsoft Login
10. Event-Driven Processing

Certain operations are executed asynchronously.

Examples include:

Appointment confirmation notifications
Appointment reminders
Payment confirmations
Laboratory report notifications
PDF generation
AI processing (future)

This approach improves application responsiveness while ensuring reliable background execution.

11. External Integrations

Current integrations planned:

Payment Gateway
Email Service
SMS Service
WhatsApp Service

Future integrations:

Insurance Providers
Pharmacy Systems
Laboratory Chains
Government Healthcare Platforms
AI Platforms
12. Security Architecture

The platform enforces security at multiple layers.

Authentication

JWT
Refresh Tokens

Authorization

Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)

Data Security

Password Hashing
HTTPS
Encryption in transit
Encryption at rest

Operational Security

Audit Logging
Tenant Isolation
Secure File Storage
13. Scalability Strategy

Clinora is designed to grow incrementally.

Initial Stage
Single application instance
Single database
Growth Stage
Multiple backend instances
Background workers
Distributed caching
Enterprise Stage
Kubernetes
Horizontal scaling
Read replicas
AI services
API Gateway
Multi-region deployment

This staged approach avoids unnecessary complexity in the MVP while allowing future expansion.

14. Design Principles

The architecture should remain:

Simple
Maintainable
Secure
Observable
Scalable
Extensible

New business modules should be added with minimal impact on existing functionality.

15. Non-Functional Considerations

The architecture should support:

High availability
Fault tolerance
Monitoring
Logging
Performance optimization
Disaster recovery
Secure backups
Compliance requirements
Document Summary

This document defines the logical architecture of the Clinora platform. It explains how users interact with the application, how business modules are organized, and how data flows through the system.

It intentionally avoids cloud-provider implementation details. Infrastructure design, networking, deployment, Kubernetes, AWS services, CI/CD, monitoring, and disaster recovery are covered in the next document.
